<HEADLINE>
<P>
THE PRESS; PENNING OPINIONS OF A TROUBLED MISSION 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
 In the Bosnian conflict, a war that defies diplomatic solutions and continues 
a bloody path that has taken an estimated 200,000 lives, the world's editorial 
cartoonists have found little but despair.In recent days the target of their 
pens has been the U.N. peacekeeping force, which, with its civilian leaders, 
has been needled for its apparent ineffectiveness. 
</P>
<P>
 Monday, Bosnian President Alija Izetbegovic complained to the Western powers 
and Russia that "nothing is being undertaken" to suppress the Serbian assault 
on the Muslim safe zone of Bihac. 
</P>
<P>
 "The whole international community, embodied in the United Nations and the 
mighty NATO pact, cannot save one endangered city," he complained. 
</P>
