<TEXT>
<P>
 At Syria's urging, Prime Minister Rafik Hariri agreed Monday to stay in power, 
defusing the worst political crisis in Lebanon since civil war ended four years 
ago. 
</P>
<P>
 The decision followed 2 1/2 hours of talks with President Hafez Assad of Syria 
and underscored his control over Lebanon. 
</P>
<P>
 Political corruption scandals and Cabinet rifts pushed Hariri to resign 
Thursday. But aides, speaking on condition of anonymity, said Monday that he 
would return home to resume his duties. 
